Linux Fundamentals Part 1 - My Notes

Completed the "Linux Fundamentals Part 1" room on TryHackMe. Here’s what I actually learned:

1. What is Linux & Why Use It
   Linux is just another OS like Windows or MacOS. But it’s way more popular for servers, Android, smart cars, traffic lights, supercomputers. 
   Main reason: It’s lightweight, open-source, and stable. Ubuntu Server can run on just 512MB RAM.
   Linux = umbrella term. Lots of "flavours" or distros based on UNIX. Ubuntu & Debian are most common. We used Ubuntu in this room.

2. Where You Interact: The Terminal
   No GUI on most servers. You use the "Terminal" - a pure text-based interface. 
   Looks scary at first: tryhackme@linux1:~$ 
   But it’s just a place to type commands. Once you know 5-6 commands, it feels normal.

3. First 2 Commands I Learned
   echo: Prints whatever text I give it. Example: echo "hello" -> prints hello
   whoami: Tells me which user I’m currently logged in as. Super useful if you use sudo or switch users.

4. Navigating the Filesystem - Most Important Part
   In Linux, everything is a file. To move around I used:
   ls: listing - shows all files/folders in current directory
   cd: change directory - moves me into a folder. Example: cd Desktop
   pwd: print working directory - tells me where I am right now
   cat: concatenate - used to read contents of a file. Example: cat notes.txt

   Trick: Directories can have directories inside them. So you go deeper with cd folder1/folder2

5. Finding Stuff with 'find'
   Instead of clicking through folders like Windows, use find.
   If I know the name: find -name passwords.txt
   It searches all subfolders and gives path: ./folder1/passwords.txt
   If I only know extension: find -name "*.txt" 
   The * is a wildcard. Means "anything". So it finds all .txt files.

6. Shell Operators - Level Up Your Commands
   & : Runs command in background. Good for long tasks so terminal doesn’t freeze.
   && : Run second command only if first one succeeds. Example: cd folder1 && ls
   > : Redirector. Takes output of a command and puts it in a file. Overwrites file. Example: echo "hi" > new.txt
   >> : Same as > but it appends instead of overwriting. Safer. Example: echo "line2" >> new.txt

7. The Lab Machine Stuff
   THM gives an in-browser Ubuntu machine. Click "Start Lab Machine". 
   You get IP, expiry time. Important: Click "Terminate" when done or it eats your free hours.
   IP was 10.10.144.238 in my case. Used for SSH but here we used browser terminal.

8. Key Takeaways from Part 1
   - Learned why Linux is everywhere even if we don’t see it.
   - Got comfortable with terminal basics. No mouse needed.
   - echo, whoami, ls, cd, pwd, cat, find are the bread and butter.
   - Operators like && and >> save time and make you look pro.
